<TITLE> European stocks reverse early losses as banks rise </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 PARIS, Jan 14 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - European stocks reversed early losses on Monday and eked out a slim gain as banking shares bounced back from recent hefty losses, eclipsing a drop in utility stocks as news of a placement hit Suez and Gaz de France. At 0912 GMT, the FTSEurofirst 300 index of top European shares was up 0.04 percent at 1,429.4 points. Europe's benchmark index has lost about 5 percent since the start of 2008, hit by worries over the prospect of a US recession. "We were expecting a spate of negative news at the start of the year, and we've been served," said Arthur van Slooten, strategist at Societe Generale, in Paris. "We're getting close to a point where the US economy could tip into recession. But we still expect some growth in the second half of the year, and the good news is that the Fed seems open to the idea that further rate cuts might be needed as they understand what's at stake." French utility Suez dropped 3.2 percent after Credit Agricole said it would sell a 2.07 percent stake in the firm, worth a potential 1.25 billion euros ($1.85 billion). Gaz de France, which is merging with Suez, was down 4 perce
